subSection.paragraph:
The first Mantel test, involving all sampled populations, revealed a positive correlation between genetic diversity and altitude (R =0.386; 
p
= 0.047). The second Mantel test utilized only the altitude and FST values of North (
700–900 m
) and MrBH (
>
1350 m
) populations and revealed a strong positive correlation between genetic diversity and altitude (R = 0.942; 
p
= 0.027). In addition to Mantel tests, MrBH populations presented many private alleles (
Table 2
), showing a unique genetic contribution in a population, with implications for species conservation (
Kalinowski, 2004
).

Populations found at high altitudes (above 
1350 m
) are genetically different from populations found at altitudes below 
1300 m
. The analysis of population structure (
Fig. 6
) shows that MrBH 01 (
1498 m
) and MRBH 02 (
1366 m
) populations were genetically distinct from North populations (
Tables 2
and 
3
), contributing to the genetic divergence of 

L. pinaster

. Altitude is one of the geographical factors with the greatest impact on the diversity of native populations, culminating in the appearance of different genetic population patterns (
Günther et al., 2016
; 
Guo et al., 2016
; 
Meena et al., 2016
). Populations found at high altitudes show high genetic diversity (
Lian et al., 2018
), increasing their ability to adapt to the biotic and abiotic factors (
Zhao et al., 2016
), leading to the emergence of local adaptations (García-Fernandez´et al., 2012). The high genetic diversity and structure of MrBH 

L. pinaster

are caused by high altitudes, selecting distinct genetic pools. Altitude variations have been demonstrated to provide a strong population structure leading to distinct genetic pools in species (García-Fern´andez et al., 2012; 
Zhao et al., 2016
).

The characterization of essential oils chemical compositions was conducted on populations from the North and MrBH, corresponding to five populations and 82 individuals; the composition of essential oils from the Campos das Vertentes population was previously reported (
Reis et al., 2010
).

Procedures for describing 

L. pinaster

diversity and population structure were performed via STACKS v.2.45, using the 
ctacks
software (
Catchen et al., 2013
; 
Cordeiro et al., 2019
; 
Zucchi et al., 2019
). Allele frequency, nucleotide diversity (π), number of alleles (A), private alleles (
Ap
), observed heterozygosity (
Ho
), expected heterozygosity (
He
), observed homozygosity, expected homozygosity, and the pairwise inbreeding coefficient (FST) were estimated using the 
cstacks
software. Tests for deviation from the Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium (HWE) for proportions in each population were performed using the 
pegas
package (
Paradis, 2010
). The hierarchical analysis of molecular variance (AMOVA) was performed with eight populations considering 19999 permutations. Individuals were grouped by the ADMIXTURE v1.2 software, and the best value of inferred populations (
K
) was implemented by the cross-validation method (
Alexander et al., 2009
). 
K
values describe genetic clusters of 

L. pinaster

populations.

The Bayesian approach using the BayeScan software v. 2.1 (
Foll and Gaggiotti, 2008
; 
Fischer et al., 2011
) and the PCAdapt model (
Luu et al., 2017
; 
Zucchi et al., 2019
) was chosen to identify the presence of SNPs under positive selection. The Bayesian approach can identify the allelic frequency of different populations and indicate which loci are under neutral selection and which are under positive selection according to the geographical distance between populations (
Foll and Gaggiotti, 2008
; 
Zucchi et al., 2019
). The model is a logistic regression based on the overall pairwise fixation coefficient (FST) values, capable of dividing the

Climatic variables (
Table S3
) altitude (
alt
), cloud cover (
cld
), diurnal temperature variation (
dtr
), max temperature (
tmx
), minimum temperature (
tmn
), evapotranspiration (
pet
), rainfall (
pre
), vapor pressure (
vap
), and relative humidity (
wet
) were obtained through CRU TS v.4.04 data deposited on the worldclim.org website (
Harris et al., 2020
). Climatic variables were obtained using the 
ncdf4
(
Pierce, 2019
) and 
raster
(
Hijmans, 2020
) packages implemented using the 
R
software (R version 4.0.2). Values of climatic variables were chosen according to the month and year of collection of each population.

The current study was conducted via a completely randomized design, and individuals of each population were considered sample units. The yield values per individual were tested by analysis of variance (
p <
0.05) and Tukey’ s test (p
>
0.05) using the 
stats
package of the 
R
software (R version 4.0.2). The yield values of essential oils and the altitude (m) of each individual were subjected to Kendall’ s correlation analysis (R, p 
<
0.05) using the 
stats
package. The total data matrix containing the chemical composition of essential oils of 

L. pinaster

individuals, climatic variables, and altitude were normalized and subjected to principal component analysis (PCA) using the 
FactoMineR
package (Le ˆet al., 2008) and hierarchical cluster analysis (HCA) with Euclidean distance and Ward link using the 
factoextra
package (
Kassambara and Mundt, 2020
) provided by the Ward algorithm. The heatmap analysis of chemical composition was performed on MetaboAnalyst (5.0) (
Chong and Xia, 2018
), which works in R language, using Euclidean distance measure and clustering by Ward algorithm. Genetic diversity was performed by STACKS v.2.45, using 
ctacks
software (
Catchen et al., 2013
; 
Cordeiro et al., 2019
; 
Zucchi et al., 2019
) and 
pegas
package (
Paradis, 2010
). Chi squared tests by each population was performed by 
hierfstat
package (
Goudet and Jombart, 2020
). Genetic structure was evaluated by AMOVA with 
poppr
package (
Kamvar et al., 2014
) and ADMIXTURE v1.2 software (
Alexander et al., 2009
). The description of SNPs under positive selection was performed by BayeScan (
Foll and Gaggiotti, 2008
; 
Fischer et al., 2011
) and PCAdapt with 
pcadapt
package (
Luu et al., 2017
; 
Zucchi et al., 2019
). Mantel tests (R, p 
<
0.05) using the 
ade4
package (
Dray and Dufour, 2007
) were performed between geographical distances (
Table S3
) and the genetic distances expressed by the fixation indexes (FST) of each population. Two Mantel tests were carried out between genetic matrixes (FST) and the altitudes of each population to determine the effects of altitude on the genetic diversity of 

L. pinaster

.
